the unlikely choice of Tobey Maguire for his hit &quot;Spider-Man,&quot; Petersen said he is seeking actors who can offer complex emotions as well as six-pack abs. <br><br>&quot;Everything after September 11 is different,&quot; he said. &quot;You want to change the image of these superheroes.&quot; <br><br>In particular, Petersen pointed to &quot;The Bourne Identity&quot; star Matt Damon as &quot;an interesting action man and a hell of an actor.&quot; <br><br>The filmmaker cited early 2003 as a realistic start date, with plans for five or six months of shooting. <br><br>Whatever battle the two superheroes face, it probably won't be as brutal as the one Warners has tackled in trying to revive its &quot;Superman&quot; franchise. <br><br>In April 1998, after spending millions on scripts and director attachments, studio worldwide production president Lorenzo di Bonaventura pulled the plug on &quot;Superman Lives&quot; during pre-production. Despite a prodigious investment of time and money, the project suffered from a bloated budget and less-than-airtight script. <br><br>However, Petersen emphasized that his film is not a continuation of the previous series, last brought to the big screen in 1987's &quot;Superman IV: The Quest for Peace.&quot; <br><br>Similarly, development continues on a standalone &quot;Superman&quot; with &quot;Charlie's Angels&quot; director McG, writer J.J. Abrams and producer Jon Peters, as well as Darren Aronofsky and Frank Stack's &quot;Batman: Year One.&quot; <br><br>Petersen is attached to a number of other projects at Warner Bros. These include the Orson Scott Card sci-fi series &quot;Ender's Game&quot; and &quot;Ender's Shadow&quot; as well as the epic &quot;The Trojan War.&quot; He said his interest in those projects continues. <br><br>&quot;It was just too exciting to me not to do 'Batman vs. Superman' now,&quot; he said. &quot;It's good to have a handful of projects cooking in your drawer. Let's see what happens after this.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usnootay.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Snootay</A> at: 7/9/02 3:53:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/udaraden.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daraden</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Soldier of Rallos Zek</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#333333>(7/9/02 4:38:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=215.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~anson357/images/daraden.jpg HEIGHT=160 WIDTH=140></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Batman &gt; Superman</span><hr size=1> Hey there was an animated version of something similar called Worlds Greatest with Batman and Superman having to deal with Joker and Luthor.  One of the COOLEST things about it was how they discovered each others identities.  <br><br>During a fight, where Bats uses his martial arts skill to thwart Superman, then whips out a small peice of Kryptonite, Superman uses his X-Ray vision to see Bruce Waynes face.  They resolve their issue of the moment and Supes goes to fly off, but not before having a tracking beacon tossed on to his cape by Bats.<br><br>Later that night Clark is lying in the bed and hears a noise at his window.  He gets up and pulls the curtain aside to see whats up.  Nothing in the immediate vicinity, he uses his telescopic vision and sees Bats about a mile away on a rooftop with binoculars.  Bats waves, then turns and jumps off the building into the darkness, Clarks secret identity revealed.<br><br>Now obviously, even for a cartoon, the writing was excellent and the storyline as well.  If they can bring that kind of material to this movie, IF it makes the big screen, then it might be ok.  Guess I will take a wait and see attitude.  I've loved comics and superheroes for nearly 35 years, and the recent resurgence of comic material to the big screen has been a vast improvement over past efforts (Spiderman and X-Men as opposed to Dolph Lundgren in the Punisher and that crappy Captain America that came out in the 70's hehe).  I'll give it a chance.<br><br>Now, let's be fully honest.  If Supes wasn't such a goody goody he would beat the living snot out of Batman.  But because he isn't willing to fight dirty like Bats (and don't get me wrong, I love Bats hehe) that's what makes him &gt; that Supes, at least in a head to head match up. <p><html><body><div align="center">  <center>  <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; text-align: center" bordercolor="#111111" id="AutoNumber3" bgcolor="#000000">    <tr>      <td><a target="_blank" href="http://www.sofeq.com/">    <img border="0" src="http://home.earthlink.net/~anson357/images/sofburn.gif" width="110" height="96"></a></td>      <td><font face="Verdana" size="2"><b><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=91680">    <font color="#99CCFF">Baron Daraden Ironfang</font></a><font color="#FFFFFF"><br>      Warlord of Rallos Zek</font></b><font color="#FFFFFF"><br>    <b>Spirits of Fire</b> - </font></font>    <font color="#FFFFFF" face="Verdana" size="2"><b><i>Zebuxorux</i></b></font></td>      <td><b><font face="Verdana" size="2">      <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=162543">    <font color="#99CCFF">Fandadar Silverwolf</font></a><font color="#FFFFFF"><br>      50th Tribunal Shaman<br>      Spirits of Fire - </font></font>    <font color="#FFFFFF" face="Verdana" size="2">      <i>Zebuxorux</i></font></b></td>    </tr>    <tr>      <td colspan="3"><font color="#FFFFFF" size="1"><span style="font-style: italic">"The true measure of a man is how he treats someone who can do him absolutely no good." </span>      -<i>